														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2437816">
									

<p>Well, in the meantime, I've come up with my own Latin codenames just for convenience's sake.</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Quantus</strong> for <a href="/qntm-s-proposal">qntm's proposal</a>. Because, you know, &quot;qntm&quot; is obviously standing for &quot;quantum&quot;, which is a &quot;noun use of neuter form&quot; of Latin <em>quantus</em>.</li>
<li><strong><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Andreas#Latin">Andreas</a></strong> for <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/djoric-dmatix-proposal">Djoric/Dmatix's collaborative proposal</a>. Because Dmatix is the only one of the two with <a href="/dr-dmatix-s-personnel-file">an actual personnel file</a> rather than an ordinary author page, and he has the given name &quot;Andrew&quot;.</li>
<li><strong>Rogatium</strong> for <a href="/roget-s-proposal">Roget's proposal</a>. Because <em><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/roget">roget</a></em> is an actual Latin word, derived from the verb <em><a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/rogo#Latin">rogō</a></em>.</li>
<li><strong>Cactus</strong> for&#8230; well, <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/djkaktus-s-proposal">djkaktus' proposal</a>. Because <a href="/glory-to-the-overkaktus">his member page</a> only gives &quot;Kaktus&quot; as his name (the rest are all just titles).</li>
<li><strong>Castium</strong> for <a href="/kate-mctiriss-s-proposal">Kate MCTiriss's proposal</a>. Because one popular etymology for &quot;Katharine&quot; derives it from Greek <em>katharos</em> (&quot;pure&quot;), the Latin counterpart for which is <em>castus</em>.</li>
</ul>
<p>What do you think?</p>

